WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Right, thanks everyone. I hope you enjoyed an ice block over the break.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:14.000
So yeah, I'm talking about what we did at my organisation to improve our science workflows

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.000
to benefit the people we work for, which is dairy farmers.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:23.000
And hopefully out of that journey there's a few lessons that might be useful for you.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
So, a little bit about our organisation, DairyNZ.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
Our purpose is to progress a better future for dairy farmers.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
A couple of quick facts about the New Zealand dairy sector.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
We produce more milk than Wisconsin, your dairy state, not a competition.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Also more milk than California, also again not a competition.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:51.000
But there's not many people in New Zealand,

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:57.000
which means that 95% of the dairy products gets exported all over the world.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:04.000
So it's important to us that we have products that people love and enjoy

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:06.000
and are happy with how that's produced.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
So a lot of our work at DairyNZ is about how can we help our farmers

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:17.000
be more profitable, sustainable and competitive going forwards.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
So this is where I think everyone wants to be.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
They want to be a happy cow, they want to be doing useful work

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
and having the tools that are fit for purpose.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:32.000
And I can't say we're always there, but I know about five years ago

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:34.000
we looked a lot more like this.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.000
We were struggling to do what we needed to do

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:41.000
and the tools were just not fit for purpose.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:47.000
So this talk is a little bit about how we channeled some of that frustration

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:53.000
with a bit of boldness to then create change and deliver on impact.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
So why do we need to change?

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Maybe a third of you will recognise this thing.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
This is a floppy disk that holds about one meg worth of data.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:12.000
So historically, 10, 20 years ago when we were doing a farm trial,

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:14.000
we'd get a few observations per day.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:19.000
So you could have a major trial where all the data would fit

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:22.000
on about six of these floppy disks.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.000
However, today we have wearable devices.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.000
You can imagine Apple Watches for cows.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:33.000
Devices like this are generating 60 observations a second

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:39.000
and you're putting this across hundreds and sometimes thousands of cows

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
and that's generating a metric crap tonne of data.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.000
And so if you put all the data for a three-month trial today onto floppy disks,

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:53.000
the tower of floppy disks would be taller than the Burj Khalifa,

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.000
like the tallest building in the world.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Also at the same time, we had to move from linear science

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:07.000
in the sense of scientists would have an experiment,

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
they'd run the experiment, they'd throw some data at the statistician,

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:15.000
produce some plots and some tables, publish it, job done.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.000
But when we're looking at this more complex data,

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
it becomes more iterative in the sense of looking at the data,

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:23.000
understanding what it's trying to tell us,

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.000
come up with some hypotheses, test those.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.000
So a very different way of working.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
So these are not all the reasons,

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.000
but these were a couple of the obvious reasons that created

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
that burning platform for why we needed to do something different.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.000
So we did three things.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
The first thing was around infrastructure.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:48.000
So if you've opened the R for Data Science book,

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
this diagram's probably quite familiar.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.000
Anyone that's got R can get started and use this workflow.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.000
But when you want to work at scale, you want to add a few things.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:01.000
So for us, we've got a data platform.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.000
We chose Snowflake.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
You might choose Databricks or something else.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
For sharing code and versioning code, we use GitHub.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Again, there's other options there.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.000
When the smoke is starting to pour out of your laptop,

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:17.000
it's time to move that compute to the cloud.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
So we use Posit Workbench for that.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.000
And then when we've created artifacts, tools, dashboards, et cetera,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.000
that we want to share, then we push that through to Posit Connect.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.000
So what guided some of those choices?

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
Well, it needed to be fit for purpose,

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.000
and for us, that meant performance.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.000
It needed to be scalable,

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:40.000
as we did more and more of this type of work,

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
and reproducible is just really good practice.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
Also, we're starting from a low base,

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
so we want a relatively low cost to start.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.000
So some open-source tools fit the bill there.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:57.000
And you also need ease of management by your IT.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
So that forms part of your total cost of ownership.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
You're going to need some confidence in the vendor,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
but you also want to limit the technological lock-in

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:14.000
wherever possible, so you have options down the future.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
You know, the landscape might change.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:20.000
For us, support for R and Python,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.000
we're primarily R now, but I could see there are some things

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:26.000
we might want to use Python for in the future,

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.000
and depending on where you're at and what your situation is,

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.000
you might make different choices.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And so this involves spending money,

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
so you're going to need some allies from around the organization,

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
extra points if you get IT on board,

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
and then you're going to have to get the senior buy-in.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
They're the people that are going to be writing the checks

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:51.000
for some of this stuff.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.000
So the second of three things, the skills and capability.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:58.000
So when we were starting down this journey,

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:02.000
we ran R for data science as an internal course.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:06.000
We ran it as a cohort, so a bunch of people

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:09.000
all learning at the same time,

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.000
and the temptation is whenever you're doing something

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:15.000
in that setting that you try and just jam it all into,

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:17.000
like, say, three days.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:19.000
We'll bring everyone in, smash them full of knowledge,

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
and then job done.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.000
But I took from the, what was the R studio education piece

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
that they used to have around the space learning,

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
which is to say, you know, if you learn a bit this week,

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.000
then you've got time to digest it and use it,

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:37.000
and then more the next week, et cetera.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.000
So that space learning as a concept, I think, is quite useful.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:47.000
You know, there was a few pros and cons to running it externally,

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
and we decided to go external for subsequent versions

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.000
and ran it through the university.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.000
The things I like about doing it externally

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
is that you're getting some commitment

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.000
from both the person and the manager.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.000
Even though it doesn't cost a lot,

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.000
you know, the fact that it actually costs something

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
means that that person and manager have to have a discussion

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
and they have to agree that this is a priority for this person,

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
and that means putting aside time to do it properly,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:18.000
which is not necessarily what happened

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
when we had an internal course.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.000
And if people got busy, then if it wasn't a priority,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.000
it didn't happen.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.000
I also like the summative assessment,

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:29.000
so assessment at the end of the course,

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:32.000
which is to say, you know, people understand,

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
you know, most of these people have been to university,

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
so they understand that, you know,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
there's going to be a test at the end

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
and they're going to have to have some minimum level of knowledge

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
in order to pass that and not be embarrassed in front of their peers.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.000
So I like that.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:49.000
Working with the university, though,

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:52.000
you do have to get on the same page

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:55.000
because, you know, they might have different ideas

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.000
about how they want to teach it

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:02.000
and what's the place of AI tools in terms of teaching it.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:06.000
From our perspective, like, we were quite pro-AI tools.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
You know, we want the people to learn something,

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
but when they're in the workplace,

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.000
they're going to be using AI tools,

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
so we want them to learn how to work with AI tools

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
as part of that process.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
So one of the things here is, you know,

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.000
we tried internally, it didn't work.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
So in this case, you know, motion, like trying something,

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
if it doesn't work, you try it a different way,

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
but just having that motion towards where you want to be

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.000
is important.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:38.000
We did do internal stats course

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:42.000
for a smaller subset that needed that extra statistical knowledge,

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:45.000
and then we ran GitHub and Snowflake lessons as well

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:49.000
so that people could understand the whole piece.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:52.000
And then the third of the three things,

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
to have a bit of business discipline

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
around how we use these tools

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.000
and that continuous improvement mindset.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.000
And often people can forget to celebrate the wins,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
but when people do something cool,

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
you know, you want to acknowledge that

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
and, you know, even say, that's cool.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.000
Or when you're helping someone with something

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
and they've overcome a barrier,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:17.000
then, you know, we want to really recognize that.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.000
That keep learning piece,

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:24.000
so we run our own internal R community.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
You know, we have external speakers come in

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
and we have some, you know, colleagues that we work with externally

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:32.000
that come to that as well.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
And we want to have a place where people can,

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
if not learn best practice,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
then at least learn good practice.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:43.000
And so we have this internal getting started book

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:46.000
where, you know, that's the first port of call

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
when they have a question.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
You know, you can of course go to other people afterwards,

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.000
but, you know, if a lot of the key knowledge is there,

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
then that saves, you know, friction and time

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.000
between going around and asking people

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.000
because often it ends up being the same people.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
So that's what we did.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And persistence, persistence is important.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.000
It's always easy when you're short of time,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
for yourself or your colleagues, you know,

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
to start taking shortcuts,

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
but that's not the way for, you know, long-term performance.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.000
So we want to think beyond our next deadline.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
We want to think about, you know,

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.000
what's best for us over our lifetime of work.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
So what have we delivered?

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:34.000
Some use cases that, you know, might be interesting.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:39.000
So we wanted to really collect quality data.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
So here we've got someone out in the field

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:46.000
collecting pasture data by cutting pasture

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
for our calibrations,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
which is great when it's sunny.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
It's not always sunny outside,

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
and then so you drop it in a puddle

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
and then someone rides the motorbike over the top.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
You can imagine what that does for data quality.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
So what we've moved to is basically

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
digital first data entry

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
with a ruggedized device in the paddock,

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
so built an app so that we could

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
get that data digital first

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.000
and then boom, it's off to snowflake pretty quickly.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
When you start having data

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
in close to real time,

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
then you can start doing reports with it.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.000
So when we do a trial or experiment,

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.000
we might have cows, you know,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.000
this group of cows

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.000
on what we call a mini-farm or a farmlet,

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
and these cows on another mini-farm,

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
they might be fed different things, for example,

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
and you want to understand how that's going.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
You can have these

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
markdown or quarto reports

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
where the scientist and the

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:51.000
technical team on the ground

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.000
can see what's happening to feed supply,

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
what's happening to milk production, etc.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:59.000
and get that real time feedback

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
and make sure that you're keeping an eye

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
on everything that needs to be working.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
Another thing we do

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:09.000
is get information to farmers.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
So this is a project

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
Connected Farm. So you can see this farmer here,

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:15.000
it's early in the day

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.000
and they're thinking about, well, what's this day

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
going to be like? Is it going to be

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
particularly hot? Do we think the cows

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
might be, you know,

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
experiencing some heat stress later

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
in the day?

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:29.000
So we did some, you know,

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.000
experimental work with a device

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
that measured the internal temperature of the cow.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.000
We had our weather station,

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
did a predictive model, and then

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
that's a prototype delivering

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
that to a phone

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.000
or via a dashboard there

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
so that the farmer

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
can start putting in interventions

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.000
if it is going to be a risk

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.000
of heat stress.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.000
Other tools

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.000
for farmers. So historically

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.000
a lot of our economic

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.000
information,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
you know, we'd collect information

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
from thousands of farms

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
and at the end of the

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
financial year we'd start doing a

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
building report on that and create

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
a PDF report.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
A PDF report is

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
okay, I guess, particularly

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.000
when a lot of people want it in hard copy.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:19.000
But we move to

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
a markdown

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
and we'll move to

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.000
quarto eventually to

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
deliver an interactive report, which is substantially

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
better. But then once

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
we'd done that mechanics to build

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
an interactive report, it was only

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
then another step to go to something

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
more forward looking. So we could build

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
in a forecast and so

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
now we've got on our website

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:43.000
a shiny

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:45.000
dashboard that

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
farmers can refer to to see how

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
costs are tracking

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
for different regions and

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
people are using the same

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
ownership structure and then they can start

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
digging into the line items for those costs

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
to see what's happening

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
across the country.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.000
And then

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
a final example

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.000
in terms of strategic management.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.000
So we have

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
farmers that are thinking

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
about, okay, what do we need to do for the long

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:15.000
term? And quite

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.000
topical is around greenhouse gas

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
emissions and how do we

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
reduce the footprint per unit

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.000
of product? But we still

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:25.000
want these farmers to be profitable.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
So we

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
did some work with Fonterra, so

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
Fonterra processes about

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
80% of the milk in New Zealand, a large

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
cooperative owned by farmers,

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
and where we wanted to be

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
we wanted to understand about the farms

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
that were in this, what we call, quadrant

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.000
one. The farms that are high for profitability

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.000
but have that low emissions

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.000
intensity of production or

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.000
low greenhouse gas emissions per unit

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
of product.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
And so when we looked at that data

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.000
we found that

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
these

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
high profit, low emissions intensity

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
farms were basically scattered all

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
over the region. So this region

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.000
is one of our main dairy regions in

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
the South Island. And the good news

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
is that you don't have to be in

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
a particular place

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
to achieve this

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
low emissions and high profitability.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
It is

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
decisions that you can make

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
to either be in that place

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.000
or move towards that place. So every

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
farmer has an opportunity

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:27.000
to do better in that space.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.000
So yeah,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
that was really a tremendous piece of work.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:33.000
So

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.000
when you identify

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
a problem as

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:39.000
we identified a problem with what we were

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.000
doing, problems need a someone.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
Someone

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.000
could be me or someone could be you.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
Some of the key

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
tips I took away from this experience

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.000
is that motion

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.000
so that moving towards where you

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
want to be was far more important

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
than waiting until everything

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:59.000
was perfect and all your ducks were

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
in a row. As long as you're

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
moving in the right direction, that's a great

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.000
start.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.000
If you want to get that scale

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
across your organisation,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
the vision is great, but I

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
think you need these other two things, the allies

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:15.000
so you've got

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.000
all people asking for

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
the same thing and then getting that

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:21.000
senior buy-in. As I said,

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.000
they're the people that are going to write the checks for

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:25.000
the infrastructure that you need.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
It's

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
great to have a plan.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
My experience

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
is that you also need a lot

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.000
of persistence if you want to get to

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
that impact.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:39.000
The bad news is that

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.000
you may well, like

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
me, need more persistence than you would

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.000
hope that it would have required.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:47.000
Either way, it's going to need some persistence.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.000
In summary, I would

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:53.000
say we're all

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
someones. If we identify

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
a problem, we can all

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
plausibly, I think,

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.000
have much more impact than

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
we realise if we

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
really pull together a plan and put

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
some back and persistence

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
in behind it. Thank you.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
APPLAUSE

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.000
Thank you, Mark.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:19.000
We have time for a few questions.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.000
The first question

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
is from Scott. What are

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
one or two surprising or

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.000
unexpected insights you had in managing

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:31.000
a departmental change to use

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
deposit products, asking from

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.000
an organisation going through a similar

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
process?

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
Actually, some of the more

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
surprising things were just recently when

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
we looked to test some

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:47.000
options. Could we

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
more tightly integrate Snowflake

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
and Posit

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
Workbench, for example, to reduce that

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
credential overhead

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.000
of one

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.000
cloud thing talking to another cloud thing?

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
We've had

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
some success to that, and I think that's part

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:05.000
of our where we'll

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:07.000
go in the future.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:09.000
You've got to be quite

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:11.000
clear on what your requirements are.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.000
For example,

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.000
Connect in Snowflake

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
at the moment doesn't allow

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.000
for

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.000
public-facing

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
products, dashboards,

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
etc. That's a key piece of what

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:27.000
we do.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.000
Just be clear on your requirements

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
and

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.000
you'll find the right tool and you'll find

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:35.000
the right combination of tools.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
All right. Thank you.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.000
Another question from Jorge.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
What advantages are there

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
in using Posit Workbench for cloud

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
computing versus using Snowflake

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.000
or Databricks?

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
If it's just

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
aggregation, filtering, etc.,

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
you can push a lot of that compute

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.000
back to Snowflake, but when you

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:57.000
want to do simulation

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
based stuff,

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:01.000
there's some things that

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:03.000
you can't push back to

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.000
Snowflake because it's

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.000
not designed to do that.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
Where

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
possible, absolutely push it back to Snowflake.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
I think that's the most efficient

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
and cost-effective way for the data

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.000
compute, but for the

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.000
simulation or more complex stuff,

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
you're still going to need a chunky

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:23.000
thing on the other end.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
It depends on what your needs are.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
All right. Thank you.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
That's all the time we have for now. A round of applause

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.000
please for Mark.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
Thank you.

